[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Java annotations**\n\nI’m thinking about quick Java compilation with an anonymous class implementing an annotation. I’ve run into the idea that annotation interfaces can’t be directly instantiated. For example, creating `new SuppressWarnings(){...}` seems illegal. It’s clear that annotation types are abstract and can’t be instantiated, but with an anonymous class, maybe it’s possible after all.\n\nStackOverflow mentions that while I can’t instantiate an annotation, I can manually implement its interface. If so, that should work and invoke the method without direct reflection in the test.\n\n**Exploring dynamic access classes**\n\nI’m considering that the dynamic-access class is active, but not in the test. The use of `$` in test class names is typically discouraged, even though anonymous classes produce that symbol. It seems important to keep the dynamic access coverage mapping to one test class file per report. \n\nI’m thinking about defining an annotation interface nested with `@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)`, although it may not be necessary for a manual instance. I also need to clarify if a value method is required. If I’m testing `getExpressionFromAnnotation`, I might not need `LanguageAnnotation`.\n\n**Inspecting user-code-filter**\n\nIt seems that the user-code-filter might only be filtering org.apache.camel, which should be fine. I don’t believe there’s an issue there. However, it might need some metadata for the test annotation in native contexts; I think that's where the agent collects information. So, I’ll take a closer look at the user-code-filter to understand it better and see if there's anything I need to adjust.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0506221318b8f7e20169fcc220d2e88193be2365eeb3b22a51\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_MI3LPpQZ_I2XZ8_SMz_GTL27BtaZ1lW4K0sI_3hYe0EDpVu5Qn-oDPSiX4TzQ3mRTJazsWTf